## 1. Slices

A **slice** is Go’s main flexible sequence type. The Go docs say slices wrap arrays to provide a more useful interface, and most array programming in Go is done with slices instead of plain arrays. ([Go][2])

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    favoriteFoods := []string{"apple", "papaya", "dragonfruit"}
    fmt.Println(favoriteFoods)
}
```

Access by index:

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    favoriteFoods := []string{"apple", "papaya", "dragonfruit"}
    fmt.Println(favoriteFoods[0])
    fmt.Println(favoriteFoods[2])
}
```

Add an item with `append`:

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    favoriteFoods := []string{"apple", "papaya", "dragonfruit"}
    favoriteFoods = append(favoriteFoods, "grapes")
    fmt.Println(favoriteFoods)
}
```

### Real-world examples

Web app:

```go
menuItems := []string{"Home", "Products", "Cart", "Profile"}
```

Automation:

```go
filesToProcess := []string{"report.csv", "users.csv", "sales.csv"}
```

Scientific computing:

```go
measurements := []float64{21.5, 22.1, 21.8}
```

